    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Five-string arched harps of the Masa people of central Chad, having a skin-covered soundbox and tuning pegs; played resting either on the ground or on the shoulder of the player.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000030041/Sadie, New Grove Dictionary of Musical Instruments (1984)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Arpas arqueadas de cinco cuerdas del pueblo Masa del centro de Chad , consistentes en una caja de resonancia cubierta de piel y clavijas para la afinación; se tocan ya sea haciéndolas descansar en el suelo o sobre el hombro del intérprete.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Vijfsnarige boogharpen van de Masa in centraal Tsjaad, met stemschroeven en een klankkast die is bedekt met huid; worden bespeeld terwijl ze op de grond of op de schouder van de bespeler steunen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052488/Etnomusicologisch Centrum</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指非洲查德中部地區，瑪莎人（Masa）的五弦拱形豎琴，具覆有獸皮的音箱和調音軸，放置於地上或是演奏者的肩膀上演奏。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Fünfsaitige Harfe der Massa aus dem zentralen Tschad mit einer membranbedeckten Resonanzkörper and Stimmwirbeln; gespielt, indem das Instrument entweder auf dem Boden steht oder auf der Schulter des Spielers ruht.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
